The process starts from one or a set of seed subjects, e.g., Vannevar Bush, the visionary behind the concept of hyperlink-based knowledge organization [bush1945we].
We prompt the LLM to return knowledge about this subject in the form of triples.
From the objects in the triples obtained for him, we then identify further entities using NER (e.g., MIT (affiliation) or Everett, MA (birth place)). Thus, we iteratively expand the entity graph and elicit further knowledge on the newly encountered entities [brin1998extracting]. We elaborate on the \textbf{knowledge prompting} and \textbf{NER} in the following paragraphs. Figure (ref) illustrates how in 3 hops, we arrive at entities of diverse types, such as historical event (Boston Tea Party, Manhattan Project), newspaper (The Times), and magazine (The New Republic).